[Normal] The system can normalize formatting, casing, whitespace, domain strings, LinkedIn URLs, and other machine-friendly representations. It can also create match keys for deduplication and search. What it cannot do is erase the human-readable source form. A company may have a cleaned canonical name for matching, but the raw display form is still important. The same principle applies to contact names, addresses, and any other field where the source shape matters.
[Heading 2] C.3 What should be excluded
[Normal] The platform should exclude obviously empty columns, meaningless metadata, and any field that has no practical use for search, context, or outreach. The goal is not to keep every possible bit of source noise. The goal is to keep the parts that help the company make better decisions and write better emails. Storage should support clarity, not clutter.